{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"20658fc2-dd51-497f-9fd7-b20413747e04","content":"Here's my analysis of `.template.config/template.json`:\n\n**❌ Issue found:**\n\n- **Line 9** — `\"datatype\": \"invalid-type\"` is not a valid datatype for a .NET template parameter. Valid values are: `bool`, `choice`, `float`, `int`, `hex`, `text`, and `string`.\n\n**⚠️ Recommendations:**\n\n- **Missing `identity`** — While optional, it's strongly recommended to include a unique template identity (e.g., `\"identity\": \"Test.Template\"`).\n- **Missing `$schema`** — Adding a `$schema` reference enables editor validation:\n  ```\n  \"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"\n  ```\n\nThe critical fix is changing `\"invalid-type\"` to one of the supported datatype values (e.g., `\"string\"`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fdfee982-b29f-4284-8ba7-d6eb77ad2cf3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me analyze this template.json file. This is a .NET template configuration file. Let me check it for issues:\n\n1. **`$schema`** - Missing. While not strictly required, it's best practice to include the schema reference.\n\n2. **`author`** - Present. ✓\n\n3. **`classifications`** - Present, array of strings. ✓\n\n4. **`name`** - Present. ✓\n\n5. **`identity`** - Missing. While not strictly required, it's recommended.\n\n6. **`shortName`** - Present. ✓\n\n7. **`symbols.myParam.datatype`** - Set to `\"invalid-type\"`. \n\nThe valid datatypes for .NET template parameters are `bool`, `choice`, `float`, `int`, `hex`, `text`, and `string`, so `\"invalid-type\"` won't work. The main issue here is that invalid datatype value—everything else is either present or optional.","outputTokens":606},"id":"8ea4dbeb-6afd-4455-8b51-3f60e9fd6f4f","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:41:03.647Z","parentId":"eb532dc2-651a-4286-a18c-3b8eaa5532d4"}
